    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can use <a href=\"https://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-collections/apidocs/org/apache/commons/collections4/CollectionUtils.html#containsAny-java.util.Collection-java.util.Collection-\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Apache Commons CollectionUtils</a>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>if(CollectionUtils.containsAny(list1,list2)) {  \n    // do whatever you want\n} else { \n    // do other thing \n}  \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This assumes that you have properly overloaded the equals functionality for your custom objects.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1709650,
      "reputation" : 2456,
      "user_id" : 1567953,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c8e6e5b86384bc9031eec21f49d9ef5f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "lavin",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1567953/lavin"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1344000021,
    "creation_date" : 1344000021,
    "answer_id" : 11796575,
    "question_id" : 11796371,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>faster way will require additional space . </p>\n\n<p>For example:</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>put all items in one list into a HashSet ( you have to implement the hash function by yourself to use object.getAttributeSame() )</p></li>\n<li><p>Go through the other list and check if any item is in the HashSet.</p></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>In this way each object is visited at most once. and HashSet is fast enough to check or insert any object in O(1).</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 543112,
      "reputation" : 2616,
      "user_id" : 912104,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Svo6i.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Harmeet Singh",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/912104/harmeet-singh"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 10,
    "last_activity_date" : 1344000527,
    "last_edit_date" : 1344000527,
    "creation_date" : 1344000197,
    "answer_id" : 11796628,
    "question_id" : 11796371,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>There is <strong>one method</strong> of <code>Collection</code> named <code>retainAll</code> but having some <strong>side effects</strong> for you <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Collection.html#retainAll%28java.util.Collection%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\">reference</a></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Retains only the elements in this list that are contained in the\n  specified collection (optional operation). In other words, removes\n  from this list all of its elements that are not contained in the\n  specified collection.</p>\n  \n  <p>true if this list changed as a result of the call</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Its like    </p>\n\n<pre><code>boolean b = list1.retainAll(list2);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1674288,
      "reputation" : 137,
      "user_id" : 1540144,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/920f571dcf20dfffb315d4706a9b4228?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "R-E-L",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1540144/r-e-l"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1344000459,
    "creation_date" : 1344000459,
    "answer_id" : 11796701,
    "question_id" : 11796371,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Can you define the type of data you hold ? is it big data ? is it sorted ?\nI think that you need to consider different efficiency approaches depending on the data.</p>\n\n<p>For example, if your data is big and unsorted you could try and iterate the two lists together by index and store each list attribute in another list helper. \nthen you could cross check by the current attributes in the helper lists.</p>\n\n<p>good luck</p>\n\n<p>edited : and I wouldn't recommend overloading equals. its dangerous and probably against your object oop meaning.</p>\n"
  }, {
