    "creation_date" : 1344009586,
    "answer_id" : 11799240,
    "question_id" : 11796371,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you just need to test basic equality, this can be done with the basic JDK without modifying the input lists in the one line</p>\n\n<pre><code>!Collections.disjoint(list1, list2);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>If you need to test a specific property, that's harder.  I would recommend, by default,</p>\n\n<pre><code>list1.stream()\n   .map(Object1::getProperty)\n   .anyMatch(\n     list2.stream()\n       .map(Object2::getProperty)\n       .collect(toSet())\n       ::contains)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>...which collects the distinct values in <code>list2</code> and tests each value in <code>list1</code> for presence.</p>\n"
